pposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]},{"name":"Llywelyn","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."]},{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["See Lywelyn."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ednowain ap Llewelyn Aurdorchog was born about 1040, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Llewelyn Aurdorchog \"Golden-Torqued\" ap Coel, was 37 and his mother, Efa ferch Cynfyn, was 23. He had at least 2 sons."},"et":{"circa 1040–":"umbes 1040–Surnud","1035–Male":"1035–Surnud","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1036–Male":"1036–Surnud","1038–Male":"1038–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1076–1126":"1076–1126","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1005–1065":"1005–1065","1018–Female":"1018–Surnud","1018":"1018","1005":"1005","1126":"1126","1038":"1038","1036":"1036","circa 1040":"umbes 1040","1035":"1035","1065":"1065","1076":"1076","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"circa 1040–":"noin 1040–Kuollut","1035–Male":"1035–Kuollut","1035–Female":"1035–Kuollut","1036–Male":"1036–Kuollut","1038–Male":"1038–Kuollut","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1076–1126":"1076–1126","1065–Male":"1065–Kuollut","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","1005–1065":"1005–1065","1018–Female":"1018–Kuollut","1018":"1018","1005":"1005","1126":"1126","1038":"1038","1036":"1036","circa 1040":"noi